{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"CSS Responsive Design","slug":"css-responsive-design","subject":"CSS","category":"Web Development","level":"Advanced","estimated_read_time":"15 mins","prerequisites":["CSS Media Queries","CSS Flexbox","CSS Grid"],"learning_objectives":["Concept of RWD","Viewport Meta Tag","Fluid Grids (%)","Flexible Images","Mobile First Strategy"],"theory":"Responsive Web Design (RWD) is about making web pages look good on all devices (desktops, tablets, and phones).\n\nIt involves combination of:\n1.  **Fluid Grids**: Using % instead of px.\n2.  **Flexible Images**: `max-width: 100%`.\n3.  **Media Queries**: Changing layout at breakpoints.\n4.  **Viewport Meta Tag**: Telling the browser to scale content to width.","syntax":"<!-- Mandatory for RWD -->\n<meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0\">","examples":[{"code":"img {\n  max-width: 100%;\n  height: auto;\n}","output":"Image scales down to fit the parent container but never gets bigger than original.","explanation":"Prevents horizontal scrolling on small screens."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Forgetting the viewport meta tag","correction":"Without it, mobile browsers will render the page as if it were a desktop (zoomed out tiny text).","example":"Always include <meta name=\"viewport\"...>"}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"What is the Viewport?","answer":"The user's visible area of a web page. It varies with the device.","difficulty":"Easy"}],"practice_problems":[{"problem":"Make a two-column layout turn into one-column on mobile.","hint":"Use flex-wrap: wrap.","solution":".row { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; } .col { width: 100%; } @media(min-width: 600px) { .col { width: 50%; } }","difficulty":"Hard"}],"real_world_use_cases":[{"scenario":"All Modern Webs","description":"Google penalizes non-responsive websites in search rankings.","code":""}],"exam_notes":["Always check responsiveness in Chrome DevTools Device Mode.","Do not use large fixed widths."],